[{"id": "49d58f43-2bd6-4512-9bb1-07c5bf484299", "chunk_index": 0, "text": "USER: Yo\nASSISTANT: \nIt was 2014. I remember the year because that was the summer everything fell apart, and also the summer of the Yo app. It was ridiculous. An app that did one thing: you pressed a button and it sent the word \u201cYo\u201d to someone. That was it. No text. No emojis. Just Yo.\n\nMy friends and I downloaded it as a joke. We sent Yo\u2019s back and forth until the novelty wore off, which was about ten minutes. But I kept it. I kept it because of him.\n\nWe had broken up two months before. The kind of breakup that feels like a clean break at first, a sharp snap, and then you realize the bone is still connected to all the nerves. I was told to give him space. I was told I needed to move on. I was telling myself those things, too, but my fingers kept typing his name into my phone, then deleting the message before I could hit send. What was there to say? I miss you felt too small. I think we made a mistake felt too big. I was just being me, which meant I was stuck.\n\nAnd then there was this app. A single word. It wasn\u2019t a question. It wasn\u2019t a demand. It was just a ping. A blip on a screen. I thought, maybe this is the answer. A way to say I\u2019m still here without having to say anything at all.\n\nI found his name in the list. My thumb hovered over the button. Don\u2019t be an idiot, I thought. It\u2019s just an app. But I was lonely. I was so lonely it felt like a physical weight in my chest. I pressed it.\n\nYo.\n\nThe screen went dark. I put my phone down, face down on the table, and tried to breathe. I felt pathetic. Truly, deeply pathetic. This was my new low, communicating in monosyllables like a caveman. A minute passed. Five. I was picking at a loose thread on the tablecloth, telling myself it was fine, it was nothing.\n\nThen my phone buzzed.\n\nI flipped it over. His name. The word Yo.\n\nI stared at it. A relief so sharp it hurt washed over me. He answered. He saw me. It was the smallest possible acknowledgment in the world, and it was everything. I sent one back.\n\nThat became our new language. A Yo in the morning. A Yo before I went to sleep. Sometimes, if I was having a bad day, I\u2019d send two. He never sent more than one. It was a game of emotional chicken, and I was always the first to flinch. I knew this story. I\u2019d lived it a thousand times with him, waiting for a sign that was never going to come, interpreting silence as a kind of answer.\n\nThe Yo\u2019s were our last connection. A thread stretched taut across the city, thinner every day. I was building a world on that single word, imagining what he was doing when he sent it. Waking up. Getting coffee. Lying in bed next to someone else. The thought would come and I\u2019d push it away. Don\u2019t judge. You went where your brain took you.\n\nThen one day, I sent the Yo. And nothing came back. I waited. An hour. A day. A week. The thread had snapped. I deleted the app. I thought I\u2019d feel relieved. I didn\u2019t. I just felt the silence where the buzz used to be. It was louder than any word he could have sent.", "embedding": [-0.09723323583602905, -0.03439649939537048, 0.1366661638021469, -0.0007892436115071177, 0.05865227058529854, -0.05274316668510437, 0.11555740982294083, 0.050112295895814896, 0.08288788050413132, -0.07479722797870636, 0.002775087719783187, 0.052657146006822586, -0.05611196905374527, 0.01718820072710514, 0.04909338057041168, -0.01532782893627882, 0.03479791432619095, 0.020299561321735382, -0.1367529034614563, 0.024499351158738136, 0.020976902917027473, 0.036624617874622345, -0.040572334080934525, -0.028511077165603638, 0.004130260553210974, -0.0029287890065461397, -0.11208010464906693, 0.02906317450106144, -0.08149707317352295, -0.00990293174982071, -0.0075425622053444386, 0.015869202092289925, 0.024091172963380814, 0.03283988684415817, -0.026671193540096283, 0.06592768430709839, -0.04187745973467827, 0.027141746133565903, 